The ionization energy of $\mathrm{H}_2$ can be found using the formula derived from the thermodynamic cycle: $IE(\mathrm{H}_2) = D_0(\mathrm{H}_2) + IE(\mathrm{H}) - D_0(\mathrm{H}_2^+)$, where $IE(\mathrm{H})$ is the ionization energy of a hydrogen atom, which is $13.6 \, \mathrm{eV}$.

## Step 6: Plug in the given values to calculate $IE(\mathrm{H}_2)$.
$IE(\mathrm{H}_2) = 4.478 \, \mathrm{eV} + 13.6 \, \mathrm{eV} - 2.651 \, \mathrm{eV}$.

## Step 7: Perform the arithmetic.
